{"title_page": "Ut\u00f8ya", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| image_name = Tyrifjorden map Ut\u00f8ya highlight.png\n| image_caption = Detailed map of [[Tyrifjorden]], with Ut\u00f8ya encircled in red\n| map = Norway\n| location = [[Tyrifjorden]]\n| area_km2= 0.106\n| country = [[Norway]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|60|01|25|N|010|14|53|E|region:NO_type:isle_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| country_admin_divisions_title = County\n| country_admin_divisions = [[Viken (county)|Viken]]\n| website = [http://www.utoya.no/ utoya.no]\n}}\n[[File:Ut\u00f8ya 3.JPG|thumb|Ut\u00f8ya]]\n'''Ut\u00f8ya''' ({{IPA-no|\u02c8\u0289\u0302\u02d0t\u02cc\u0153\u028f\u0251||Ut\u00f8ya.ogg}}) is an island in the [[Tyrifjorden]] lake in [[Hole, Norway|Hole]] municipality, in the county of [[Viken (county)|Viken]], [[Norway]]. The island is {{convert|10.6|ha}},<ref>Coastline for the property \"0612-235/1 Ut\u00f8en\", according to [[Statens kartverk]], http://seeiendom.no/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714034345/http://www.seeiendom.no/ |date=14 July 2011 }}</ref> situated {{convert|500|m}} off the shore, by the [[European route E16|E16]] road, about {{convert|20|km|abbr=on}} driving distance south of [[H\u00f8nefoss]], and {{convert|38|km|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Oslo]] city centre.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Ut\u00f8ya 2017-07-09-5734.jpg|thumb|The ferry [[MS Thorbj\u00f8rn]] at the arrival pier at Ut\u00f8ya. The nearest white-painted house is one of the original houses on the island.]]\nUt\u00f8ya is owned by the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|Workers' Youth League]] (''AUF''), a youth group associated with the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]], which holds an annual summer camp there.  \n\nThe island is operated commercially by Ut\u00f8ya AS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auf.no/english/286-utoya-2010-aufs-summer-camp- |title='&#39;Ut\u00f8ya 2010 \u2013 AUFs summer camp'&#39; (Arbeidernes Ungdomsfylking |publisher=Auf.no |accessdate=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904165132/http://www.auf.no/english/286-utoya-2010-aufs-summer-camp- |archivedate=4 September 2011 }}</ref> \n\nThe island is largely forested, with some open spaces. A small pier on the east side of the island is used to ferry people to and from [[Ut\u00f8ykaia]] on the mainland. There are also permanent buildings. ''Hovedhuset'' (\"The Main House\"), ''Stabburet'' (\"The [[H\u00f3rreo]]\"), and ''L\u00e5ven'' (\"The Barn\") are located together near the dock. Up on the hillside (''LO-toppen'') are the main campgrounds, the cafeteria building, and the sanitary building. ''Skolestua'' (\"The school house\") is located further south.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adressa.no/incoming/article1399644.ece5/BINARY/w980/ut%C3%B8yagrafikk|title=Ut\u00f8yagrafikk|publisher=Adressa.no|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==The name==\nThe first element ''ut'' means 'out', or 'outermost'; the last element ''\u00f8ya'' is the [[definiteness|definite]] form of ''\u00f8y'', meaning 'island'. Ut\u00f8ya is the southernmost (or farthest \"out\") island of three which lie in the lake of Tyrifjorden. The name is used in reference to its position in relation to two other islands (lying north of Ut\u00f8ya); ''Stor\u00f8ya'' (Big Isle) and ''Geit\u00f8ya'' (Goat Isle). Stor\u00f8ya is the northernmost, and Geit\u00f8ya lies between Ut\u00f8ya and Stor\u00f8ya. All of these islands were formerly used for [[herding]] (as is shown in the meaning of Geit\u00f8ya) by the people at [[Sundvollen]]. Ut\u00f8ya is quite clearly connected to the name of [[Utvika]] on the shoreside.\n\n==History==\nThe island was a [[croft (land)|croft]] until purchased by the right wing politician [[Jens Bratlie]] in 1893. Bratlie used the property as a summer residence until 1933 when it was purchased by the [[Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions|Trade Union Confederation]].<ref>Bergens tidende magasinet 21.juli 2012 s.13.</ref>\n\nThe island was given as a commemorative gift by the [[Oslo Trade Union Confederation]] on 28 August 1950,<!--Oslo Trade Union Confederation--><ref>[http://snl.no/Ut\u00f8ya Store Norske Leksikon: Ut\u00f8ya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201080302/https://snl.no/Ut%C3%B8ya |date=1 February 2017 }} Retrieved 2011-07-24</ref> and it has hosted several political organizations' summer camps.\n\n===2011 massacre ===\n{{Main article|2011 Norway attacks#Ut\u00f8ya massacre}}\n\nOn 22 July 2011, a mass shooting took place at the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|AUF]]'s summer youth camp, where 650 young people were staying. [[Anders Behring Breivik]] arrived alone on Ut\u00f8ya dressed as a police officer and told those on the island that he was there for security reasons following the explosions in Oslo which took place a few hours before.  He then began shooting at individuals, continuing until the police arrived one hour after the first alarm call. The suspect immediately surrendered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/|title=VGs fotograf havnet midt i bombedrama - hjelper skadede barn|accessdate=24 July 2011|newspaper=Verdens Gang|language=Norwegian|date=24 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929034838/http://www.vg.no/|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Combined, the attacks in Oslo and Ut\u00f8ya left 77 dead, with 69 killed on the island, 33 of whom were under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gibbs |first=Walter |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-norway-blast-idUSTRE76L2VI20110723 |title=At least 93 dead in Norway shooting, bomb attack &#124; Reuters |publisher=Uk.reuters.com |date=2011-03-31 |accessdate=2011-07-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020230740/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-norway-blast-idUSTRE76L2VI20110723 |archive-date=20 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Norway attacks: The victims  | work=[[bbc.com]] | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-14276074| accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110909043438/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/oslobomben/ofre/ Terrorofrene p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya og i Oslo]</ref>\n\n===After the massacre ===\n\"Rapidly it became clear, that ... [the bereaved] needed more time. [Construction work, or] The construction was put on hold for two years\", according to the island's manager (as of 2016), J\u00f8rgen Frydnes.<ref name=\"Manager2016\">{{cite news|author1=Astrid Hauge Ramb\u00f8l|title=Med Ut\u00f8ya som arbeidsplass|publisher=[[Klassekampen]]|date=22 July 2016|pages=28\u20139}}</ref>\n\nAfter the attack, several donations were given to AUF for the restoration of the island. Some of the buildings would be demolished, including [parts of] the cafeteria building where 13 people had been killed;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/22-juli/artikkel.php?artid=10057597 |title=Har f\u00e5tt inn 35 millioner kroner p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya-fond |date=2 May 2012 |publisher=VG |language=Norwegian |accessdate=30 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518032451/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/22-juli/artikkel.php?artid=10057597 |archivedate=18 May 2012 }}</ref> some of the buildings have been demolished, as of 2016.\n\nWith some disagreement having been bridged (as of 2016) -\nthe future of Ut\u00f8ya has been the source of disagreements among the victims and family of the attacks. While AUF's planned to [rapidly] rebuild and return to Ut\u00f8ya, others wanted to leave the island as a memorial to the dead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/samfunn/splittet-om-utoyas-framtid/|title=Splittet om Ut\u00f8yas framtid|last=Johnsrud|first=Nina|date=5 July 2012|publisher=Dagsavisen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=30 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527040250/http://www.dagsavisen.no/samfunn/splittet-om-utoyas-framtid/|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe massacre at Ut\u00f8ya remains the deadliest mass shooting worldwide committed by a single gunman.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last1=Herring |first1=Keely |last2=Jacobson |first2=Louis |title=Is Barack Obama correct that mass killings don't happen in other countries? |url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/jun/22/barack-obama/barack-obama-correct-mass-killings-dont-happen-oth/ |website=www.politifact.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Places and buildings==\n[[Bay]]s on the island's coastline include Bolsjevika.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\">{{cite news|author1=Kjell-Erik Nordenson Kallset|title=Tar tilbake Ut\u00f8ya|publisher=[[Klassekampen]]|date=1 July 2016|page=2}}</ref>\n\nThere are paths including  Kj\u00e6rlighetsstien ([lovers' lane or]\"the love path\").<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/>\n\nA hill - \"used by discussion [groups]\" leads to [a barn, according to its name,] ''Arbeidsmilj\u00f8l\u00e5ven''.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/> Other buildings are \"the caf\u00e9 building\" and the pump house.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/>\n\n[\"The hill\"] \"Bakken\" is used by the audience of speeches (as of 2016).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/den-nye-generasjonen-utoya-1.761767 |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806153836/http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/den-nye-generasjonen-utoya-1.761767 |archive-date=6 August 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n===Memorial place===\nThe place of memorial is called [\"the clearing\"] ''Lysninga'';\"it lies at the highest point of the island\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Publisert 19.07.2016, kl. 05.31. |url=https://www.nrk.no/buskerud/xl/50-turer-dagen-til-utoya-pa-det-meste-1.13044637 |title=50 turer dagen til Ut\u00f8ya p\u00e5 det meste |publisher=Nrk.no |date=2016-07-19 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720172601/https://www.nrk.no/buskerud/xl/50-turer-dagen-til-utoya-pa-det-meste-1.13044637 |archive-date=20 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was unveiled during the summer of 2015.<ref name=BereavedFearMonolithCelebratingPerp>{{cite web |author=Gabrielle Graatrud |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/etterlatte-frykter-at-22juli-minnestedet-blir-en-bauta-over-gjerningsmannen/60240778 |title=Etterlatte frykter at 22.juli-minnestedet blir en bauta over gjerningsmannen |publisher=Dagbladet.no |date=2016-06-18 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820181717/http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/etterlatte-frykter-at-22juli-minnestedet-blir-en-bauta-over-gjerningsmannen/60240778 |archive-date=20 August 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Snu>{{cite web |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2016/04/04/kultur/kronikk/meninger/debatt/sorbraten/43724033/ |title=No shame in turning around! |publisher=Dagbladet.no |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606203803/http://www.dagbladet.no/2016/04/04/kultur/kronikk/meninger/debatt/sorbraten/43724033/ |archive-date=6 June 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nComponents of the memorial place include [\"the ring\"] \"Ringen\" - a \"ring of steel [that] hangs between trees and here the names and age<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/> of the majority of those 69 killed are engraved\".\n\n\"The ring\" weighs one (metric-) ton; one part of it weighs 350 kilograms; [[Alice Greenwald]] gave advice about leaving some space on \"the ring\", so that some of the bereaved can later change their mind - so that their deceased relative's name is permitted to be engraved on \"the ring\".<ref name=\"Manager2016\"/><ref>[http://www.utoya.no/minnested About the Memorial Site 22 July at Ut\u00f8ya itself] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820203453/http://www.utoya.no/minnested |date=20 August 2018 }} utoya.no {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\n===''Hegnhuset'' (\"safeguard house\")===\n''Hegnhuset'' - consists of \"Parts of the caf\u00e9 building (''kaf\u00e9bygget '') ..., where 13 people were killed ..., [that] have been preserved (as of 2016); around- and under the caf\u00e9 building - a [\"learning center\"] ''l\u00e6ringssenter''\" has been created;<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957/ |title=Kaf\u00e9bygget p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya \u00e5pnes igjen |publisher=Vg.no |date=2016-07-19 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722080442/http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957 |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrk.no/sapmi/hegnhuset-symboliserer-de-drepte-pa-utoya-1.13047901 |title=Hegnhuset symboliserer de drepte p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya |publisher=Nrk.no |date=2016-07-18 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718112442/https://www.nrk.no/sapmi/hegnhuset-symboliserer-de-drepte-pa-utoya-1.13047901 |archive-date=18 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n69 columns support the roof,<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/> inside the glass walls (of the exterior of the building).<ref name=\"dagsavisen1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/nodvendigheten-og-minnene-1.755594 |title=N\u00f8dvendigheten og minnene |publisher=dagsavisen.no |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722121238/http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/nodvendigheten-og-minnene-1.755594 |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> 495 \"safeguarding\" planks - positioned vertical in the ground - enclose the building; with space - ''[[svalgang]]'' - between the planks and the building.<ref name=\"dagsavisen1\"/>\n\n\"The house will protect the memory of the 69 who were killed at Ut\u00f8ya\", a father (of one of the massacre's survivors) wrote in a news article.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/>\n\nEtymology: The building has been named Hegnhuset - \"a place that shall safeguard (''hegne'') democracy\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=\u00c5shild Lappeg\u00e5rd Lahn|title=Vil hindre at det skjer igjen|publisher=[[Klassekampen]]|date=18 July 2016}}</ref> A synonym of ''hegn'' is the imperative form of the verb \"safeguard\"; therefore ''Hegnhuset'' can mean \"safeguard house\" (with the determinate conjugation of \"house\").\n\nInside the caf\u00e9 building, preserved (as of 2016) are bullet holes in walls, \"the open windows where several youths jumped out to escape\" the murderer; an old chart (that was there in 2011) that says \"you must know the past, to understand the present and peer into the future\", and pictures of dead victims; at least one heart-shaped stone, with the inscription \"Missing you [singular]\", lies on the floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957/ |title=Kaf\u00e9bygget p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya \u00e5pnes igjen - VG |publisher=Vg.no |date=2016-07-19 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722080442/http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957 |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn ''lillesalen'' (\"the small hall\") there is a piano; one was there during the crime. Court testimony has indicated that persons hiding behind the piano on 22 July 2011, were shot.<ref>{{cite web |author=Av Per Erik Hagen |url=http://www.budstikka.no/nyheter/nyheter/breivik-husket-ikke-skyting-i-lillesalen-pa-utoya/s/2-2.310-1.7192507 |title=Breivik husket ikke skyting i Lillesalen p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya |publisher=Budstikka.no |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807075619/http://www.budstikka.no/nyheter/nyheter/breivik-husket-ikke-skyting-i-lillesalen-pa-utoya/s/2-2.310-1.7192507 |archive-date=7 August 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 [[Oliver Wainwright]] named it the \"top 10 buildings of 2016\", adding that \" the Hegnhuset on the island of Ut\u00f8ya makes a simple, powerful record of an event that shook the very foundations of Norway\u2019s national identity. The cafe building, where Anders Breivik murdered ... before killing a further 50 on the island, has been retained as a stark relic, its walls sliced with [[Matta-Clark]] rawness, and encased in a simple timber and glass pavilion\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/dec/05/top-10-buildings-of-2016-oliver-wainwright |title=Archived copy |access-date=16 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217031422/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/dec/05/top-10-buildings-of-2016-oliver-wainwright |archive-date=17 December 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.utoya.no/ utoya.no - The campsite Ut\u00f8ya] {{in lang|no}}\n*[http://www.utoya.no/historien utoya.no - The history of Ut\u00f8ya] (in Norwegian and in English at the bottom of the page)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111119102245/http://home.online.no/~jon-o2/index.cfm Ut\u00f8ya AS] ([[Wayback Machine]] archives) {{in lang|no}}\n*[http://www.auf.no/ Arbeidernes ungdomsfylking website] {{in lang|no}}\n\n{{2011 Norway attacks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Utoya}}\n\n[[Category:Lake islands of Europe]]\n[[Category:Islands of Viken (county)]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Norway)]]\n[[Category:Private islands]]\n[[Category:2011 Norway attacks]]\n[[Category:Hole, Norway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| image_name = Tyrifjorden map Ut\u00f8ya highlight.png\n| image_caption = Detailed map of [[Tyrifjorden]], with Ut\u00f8ya encircled in red\n| map = Norway\n| location = [[Tyrifjorden]]\n| area_km2= 0.106\n| country = [[Norway]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|60|01|25|N|010|14|53|E|region:NO_type:isle_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| country_admin_divisions_title = County\n| country_admin_divisions = [[Viken (county)|Viken]]\n| website = [http://www.utoya.no/ utoya.no]\n}}\n[[File:Ut\u00f8ya 3.JPG|thumb|Ut\u00f8ya]]\n'''Ut\u00f8ya''' ({{IPA-no|\u02c8\u0289\u0302\u02d0t\u02cc\u0153\u028f\u0251||Ut\u00f8ya.ogg}}) is an island in the [[Tyrifjorden]] lake in [[Hole, Norway|Hole]] municipality, in the county of [[Viken (county)|Viken]], [[Norway]]. The island is {{convert|10.6|ha}},<ref>Coastline for the property \"0612-235/1 Ut\u00f8en\", according to [[Statens kartverk]], http://seeiendom.no/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714034345/http://www.seeiendom.no/ |date=14 July 2011 }}</ref> situated {{convert|500|m}} off the shore, by the [[European route E16|E16]] road, about {{convert|20|km|abbr=on}} driving distance south of [[H\u00f8nefoss]], and {{convert|38|km|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Oslo]] city centre.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Ut\u00f8ya 2017-07-09-5734.jpg|thumb|The ferry [[MS Thorbj\u00f8rn]] at the arrival pier at Ut\u00f8ya. The nearest white-painted house is one of the original houses on the island.]]\nUt\u00f8ya is owned by the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|Workers' Youth League]] (''AUF''), a youth group associated with the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]], which holds an annual summer camp there.  \n\nThe island is operated commercially by Ut\u00f8ya AS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auf.no/english/286-utoya-2010-aufs-summer-camp- |title='&#39;Ut\u00f8ya 2010 \u2013 AUFs summer camp'&#39; (Arbeidernes Ungdomsfylking |publisher=Auf.no |accessdate=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904165132/http://www.auf.no/english/286-utoya-2010-aufs-summer-camp- |archivedate=4 September 2011 }}</ref> \n\nThe island is largely forested, with some open spaces. A small pier on the east side of the island is used to ferry people to and from [[Ut\u00f8ykaia]] on the mainland. There are also permanent buildings. ''Hovedhuset'' (\"The Main House\"), ''Stabburet'' (\"The [[H\u00f3rreo]]\"), and ''L\u00e5ven'' (\"The Barn\") are located together near the dock. Up on the hillside (''LO-toppen'') are the main campgrounds, the cafeteria building, and the sanitary building. ''Skolestua'' (\"The school house\") is located further south.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adressa.no/incoming/article1399644.ece5/BINARY/w980/ut%C3%B8yagrafikk|title=Ut\u00f8yagrafikk|publisher=Adressa.no|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==The name==\nThe first element ''ut'' means 'out', or 'outermost'; the last element ''\u00f8ya'' is the [[definiteness|definite]] form of ''\u00f8y'', meaning 'island'. Ut\u00f8ya is the southernmost (or farthest \"out\") island of three which lie in the lake of Tyrifjorden. The name is used in reference to its position in relation to two other islands (lying north of Ut\u00f8ya); ''Stor\u00f8ya'' (Big Isle) and ''Geit\u00f8ya'' (Goat Isle). Stor\u00f8ya is the northernmost, and Geit\u00f8ya lies between Ut\u00f8ya and Stor\u00f8ya. All of these islands were formerly used for [[herding]] (as is shown in the meaning of Geit\u00f8ya) by the people at [[Sundvollen]]. Ut\u00f8ya is quite clearly connected to the name of [[Utvika]] on the shoreside.\n\n==History==\nThe island was a [[croft (land)|croft]] until purchased by the right wing politician [[Jens Bratlie]] in 1893. Bratlie used the property as a summer residence until 1933 when it was purchased by the [[Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions|Trade Union Confederation]].<ref>Bergens tidende magasinet 21.juli 2012 s.13.</ref>\n\nThe island was given as a commemorative gift by the [[Oslo Trade Union Confederation]] on 28 August 1950,<!--Oslo Trade Union Confederation--><ref>[http://snl.no/Ut\u00f8ya Store Norske Leksikon: Ut\u00f8ya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201080302/https://snl.no/Ut%C3%B8ya |date=1 February 2017 }} Retrieved 2011-07-24</ref> and it has hosted several political organizations' summer camps.\n\n===2011 massacre ===\n{{Main article|2011 Norway attacks#Ut\u00f8ya massacre}}\n\nOn 22 July 2011, a mass shooting took place at the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|AUF]]'s summer youth camp, where 650 young people were staying. [[Anders Behring Breivik]] arrived alone on Ut\u00f8ya dressed as a police officer and told those on the island that he was there for security reasons following the explosions in Oslo which took place a few hours before.  He then began shooting at individuals, continuing until the police arrived one hour after the first alarm call. The suspect immediately surrendered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/|title=VGs fotograf havnet midt i bombedrama - hjelper skadede barn|accessdate=24 July 2011|newspaper=Verdens Gang|language=Norwegian|date=24 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929034838/http://www.vg.no/|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Combined, the attacks in Oslo and Ut\u00f8ya left 77 dead, with 69 killed on the island, 33 of whom were under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gibbs |first=Walter |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-norway-blast-idUSTRE76L2VI20110723 |title=At least 93 dead in Norway shooting, bomb attack &#124; Reuters |publisher=Uk.reuters.com |date=2011-03-31 |accessdate=2011-07-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020230740/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-norway-blast-idUSTRE76L2VI20110723 |archive-date=20 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Norway attacks: The victims  | work=[[bbc.com]] | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-14276074| accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110909043438/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/oslobomben/ofre/ Terrorofrene p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya og i Oslo]</ref>\n\n===After the massacre ===\n\"Rapidly it became clear, that ... [the bereaved] needed more time. [Construction work, or] The construction was put on hold for two years\", according to the island's manager (as of 2016), J\u00f8rgen Frydnes.<ref name=\"Manager2016\">{{cite news|author1=Astrid Hauge Ramb\u00f8l|title=Med Ut\u00f8ya som arbeidsplass|publisher=[[Klassekampen]]|date=22 July 2016|pages=28\u20139}}</ref>\n\nAfter the attack, several donations were given to AUF for the restoration of the island. Some of the buildings would be demolished, including [parts of] the cafeteria building where 13 people had been killed;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/22-juli/artikkel.php?artid=10057597 |title=Har f\u00e5tt inn 35 millioner kroner p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya-fond |date=2 May 2012 |publisher=VG |language=Norwegian |accessdate=30 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518032451/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/22-juli/artikkel.php?artid=10057597 |archivedate=18 May 2012 }}</ref> some of the buildings have been demolished, as of 2016.\n\nWith some disagreement having been bridged (as of 2016) -\nthe future of Ut\u00f8ya has been the source of disagreements among the victims and family of the attacks. While AUF's planned to [rapidly] rebuild and return to Ut\u00f8ya, others wanted to leave the island as a memorial to the dead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/samfunn/splittet-om-utoyas-framtid/|title=Splittet om Ut\u00f8yas framtid|last=Johnsrud|first=Nina|date=5 July 2012|publisher=Dagsavisen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=30 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527040250/http://www.dagsavisen.no/samfunn/splittet-om-utoyas-framtid/|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe massacre at Ut\u00f8ya remains the deadliest mass shooting worldwide committed by a single gunman.\n\n==Places and buildings==\n[[Bay]]s on the island's coastline include Bolsjevika.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\">{{cite news|author1=Kjell-Erik Nordenson Kallset|title=Tar tilbake Ut\u00f8ya|publisher=[[Klassekampen]]|date=1 July 2016|page=2}}</ref>\n\nThere are paths including  Kj\u00e6rlighetsstien ([lovers' lane or]\"the love path\").<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/>\n\nA hill - \"used by discussion [groups]\" leads to [a barn, according to its name,] ''Arbeidsmilj\u00f8l\u00e5ven''.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/> Other buildings are \"the caf\u00e9 building\" and the pump house.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/>\n\n[\"The hill\"] \"Bakken\" is used by the audience of speeches (as of 2016).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/den-nye-generasjonen-utoya-1.761767 |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806153836/http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/den-nye-generasjonen-utoya-1.761767 |archive-date=6 August 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n===Memorial place===\nThe place of memorial is called [\"the clearing\"] ''Lysninga'';\"it lies at the highest point of the island\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Publisert 19.07.2016, kl. 05.31. |url=https://www.nrk.no/buskerud/xl/50-turer-dagen-til-utoya-pa-det-meste-1.13044637 |title=50 turer dagen til Ut\u00f8ya p\u00e5 det meste |publisher=Nrk.no |date=2016-07-19 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720172601/https://www.nrk.no/buskerud/xl/50-turer-dagen-til-utoya-pa-det-meste-1.13044637 |archive-date=20 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was unveiled during the summer of 2015.<ref name=BereavedFearMonolithCelebratingPerp>{{cite web |author=Gabrielle Graatrud |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/etterlatte-frykter-at-22juli-minnestedet-blir-en-bauta-over-gjerningsmannen/60240778 |title=Etterlatte frykter at 22.juli-minnestedet blir en bauta over gjerningsmannen |publisher=Dagbladet.no |date=2016-06-18 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820181717/http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/etterlatte-frykter-at-22juli-minnestedet-blir-en-bauta-over-gjerningsmannen/60240778 |archive-date=20 August 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Snu>{{cite web |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2016/04/04/kultur/kronikk/meninger/debatt/sorbraten/43724033/ |title=No shame in turning around! |publisher=Dagbladet.no |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606203803/http://www.dagbladet.no/2016/04/04/kultur/kronikk/meninger/debatt/sorbraten/43724033/ |archive-date=6 June 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nComponents of the memorial place include [\"the ring\"] \"Ringen\" - a \"ring of steel [that] hangs between trees and here the names and age<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/> of the majority of those 69 killed are engraved\".\n\n\"The ring\" weighs one (metric-) ton; one part of it weighs 350 kilograms; [[Alice Greenwald]] gave advice about leaving some space on \"the ring\", so that some of the bereaved can later change their mind - so that their deceased relative's name is permitted to be engraved on \"the ring\".<ref name=\"Manager2016\"/><ref>[http://www.utoya.no/minnested About the Memorial Site 22 July at Ut\u00f8ya itself] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820203453/http://www.utoya.no/minnested |date=20 August 2018 }} utoya.no {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\n===''Hegnhuset'' (\"safeguard house\")===\n''Hegnhuset'' - consists of \"Parts of the caf\u00e9 building (''kaf\u00e9bygget '') ..., where 13 people were killed ..., [that] have been preserved (as of 2016); around- and under the caf\u00e9 building - a [\"learning center\"] ''l\u00e6ringssenter''\" has been created;<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957/ |title=Kaf\u00e9bygget p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya \u00e5pnes igjen |publisher=Vg.no |date=2016-07-19 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722080442/http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957 |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrk.no/sapmi/hegnhuset-symboliserer-de-drepte-pa-utoya-1.13047901 |title=Hegnhuset symboliserer de drepte p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya |publisher=Nrk.no |date=2016-07-18 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718112442/https://www.nrk.no/sapmi/hegnhuset-symboliserer-de-drepte-pa-utoya-1.13047901 |archive-date=18 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n69 columns support the roof,<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/> inside the glass walls (of the exterior of the building).<ref name=\"dagsavisen1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/nodvendigheten-og-minnene-1.755594 |title=N\u00f8dvendigheten og minnene |publisher=dagsavisen.no |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722121238/http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/nodvendigheten-og-minnene-1.755594 |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> 495 \"safeguarding\" planks - positioned vertical in the ground - enclose the building; with space - ''[[svalgang]]'' - between the planks and the building.<ref name=\"dagsavisen1\"/>\n\n\"The house will protect the memory of the 69 who were killed at Ut\u00f8ya\", a father (of one of the massacre's survivors) wrote in a news article.<ref name=\"Miljolaven\"/>\n\nEtymology: The building has been named Hegnhuset - \"a place that shall safeguard (''hegne'') democracy\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=\u00c5shild Lappeg\u00e5rd Lahn|title=Vil hindre at det skjer igjen|publisher=[[Klassekampen]]|date=18 July 2016}}</ref> A synonym of ''hegn'' is the imperative form of the verb \"safeguard\"; therefore ''Hegnhuset'' can mean \"safeguard house\" (with the determinate conjugation of \"house\").\n\nInside the caf\u00e9 building, preserved (as of 2016) are bullet holes in walls, \"the open windows where several youths jumped out to escape\" the murderer; an old chart (that was there in 2011) that says \"you must know the past, to understand the present and peer into the future\", and pictures of dead victims; at least one heart-shaped stone, with the inscription \"Missing you [singular]\", lies on the floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957/ |title=Kaf\u00e9bygget p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya \u00e5pnes igjen - VG |publisher=Vg.no |date=2016-07-19 |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722080442/http://www.vg.no/bildespesial/13957 |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn ''lillesalen'' (\"the small hall\") there is a piano; one was there during the crime. Court testimony has indicated that persons hiding behind the piano on 22 July 2011, were shot.<ref>{{cite web |author=Av Per Erik Hagen |url=http://www.budstikka.no/nyheter/nyheter/breivik-husket-ikke-skyting-i-lillesalen-pa-utoya/s/2-2.310-1.7192507 |title=Breivik husket ikke skyting i Lillesalen p\u00e5 Ut\u00f8ya |publisher=Budstikka.no |accessdate=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807075619/http://www.budstikka.no/nyheter/nyheter/breivik-husket-ikke-skyting-i-lillesalen-pa-utoya/s/2-2.310-1.7192507 |archive-date=7 August 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 [[Oliver Wainwright]] named it the \"top 10 buildings of 2016\", adding that \" the Hegnhuset on the island of Ut\u00f8ya makes a simple, powerful record of an event that shook the very foundations of Norway\u2019s national identity. The cafe building, where Anders Breivik murdered ... before killing a further 50 on the island, has been retained as a stark relic, its walls sliced with [[Matta-Clark]] rawness, and encased in a simple timber and glass pavilion\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/dec/05/top-10-buildings-of-2016-oliver-wainwright |title=Archived copy |access-date=16 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217031422/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/dec/05/top-10-buildings-of-2016-oliver-wainwright |archive-date=17 December 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.utoya.no/ utoya.no - The campsite Ut\u00f8ya] {{in lang|no}}\n*[http://www.utoya.no/historien utoya.no - The history of Ut\u00f8ya] (in Norwegian and in English at the bottom of the page)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111119102245/http://home.online.no/~jon-o2/index.cfm Ut\u00f8ya AS] ([[Wayback Machine]] archives) {{in lang|no}}\n*[http://www.auf.no/ Arbeidernes ungdomsfylking website] {{in lang|no}}\n\n{{2011 Norway attacks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Utoya}}\n\n[[Category:Lake islands of Europe]]\n[[Category:Islands of Viken (county)]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Norway)]]\n[[Category:Private islands]]\n[[Category:2011 Norway attacks]]\n[[Category:Hole, Norway]]\n", "name_user": "Stoshmaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfter the massacre:ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ut%C3%B8ya"}
{"title_page": "Giorgio Quazza Medal", "text_new": "The '''Giorgio Quazza Medal''' is an award given by the [[International Federation of Automatic Control]] (IFAC) to a distinguished control engineer, presented at each IFAC Triennial International World Congress. It was created in 1979, as a memorial to the late Giorgio Qaazza, a leading Italian electrical and control engineer who served IFAC in many capacities in a most distinguished manner. The award is given for \"outstanding lifetime contributions of a researcher and/or engineer to conceptual foundations in the field of systems and control.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ifac-control.org/awards/major-awards|title=Major Awards|publisher=[[International Federation of Automatic Control]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n{{colbegin}}\n* 1981: [[John Flavell Coales|John F. Coales]]\n* 1984: {{ill|Yakov Z. Tsypkin|ru|\u0426\u044b\u043f\u043a\u0438\u043d, \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0417\u0430\u043b\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}\n* 1987: [[Karl Johan \u00c5str\u00f6m|Karl J. \u00c5str\u00f6m]]\n* 1990: [[Petar V. Kokotovic]]\n* 1993: [[Edward J. Davison]]\n* 1996: [[Alberto Isidori]]\n* 1999: [[Brian D. O. Anderson]]\n* 2002: [[Lennart Ljung]]\n* 2005: [[Tamer Basar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/birkhauser/news?SGWID=0-40335-2-137602-0|title=Tamer Basar will receive the Giorgio Quazza Medal 2005|website=springer.com|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Graham Goodwin]]\n* 2011: [[Hidenori Kimura]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riken.jp/en/news_pubs/news/2010/20100827/|title=Hidenori Kimura wins Giorgio Quazza Medal|website=riken.jp|date=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n* 2014: [[David Mayne]]\n* 2017: [[Roger Brockett]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seas.harvard.edu/news/2016/08/roger-brockett-receive-lifetime-achievement-award|title=Roger Brockett to receive lifetime achievement award|website=harvard.edu|date=15 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2020: [[Walter Murray Wonham|W. Murray Wonham]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.utoronto.ca/news/university-professor-emeritus-murray-wonham-receives-the-giorgio-quazza-medal/|title=University Professor Emeritus Murray Wonham receives the Giorgio Quazza medal|website=utoronto.ca|date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n* [[IEEE Control Systems Award]]\n* [[Richard E. Bellman Control Heritage Award]]\n* [[Rufus Oldenburger Medal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Systems sciences awards]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Giorgio Quazza Medal''' is an award given by the [[International Federation of Automatic Control]] (IFAC) to a distinguished control engineer, presented at each IFAC Triennial International World Congress as a memorial to the late Giorgio Qaazza, a leading Italian electrical and control engineer who served IFAC in many capacities in a most distinguished manner. It was created in 1979. The award is given for \"outstanding lifetime contributions of a researcher and/or engineer to conceptual foundations in the field of systems and control.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ifac-control.org/awards/major-awards|title=Major Awards|publisher=[[International Federation of Automatic Control]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n{{colbegin}}\n* 1981: [[John Flavell Coales|John F. Coales]]\n* 1984: {{ill|Yakov Z. Tsypkin|ru|\u0426\u044b\u043f\u043a\u0438\u043d, \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0417\u0430\u043b\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}\n* 1987: [[Karl Johan \u00c5str\u00f6m|Karl J. \u00c5str\u00f6m]]\n* 1990: [[Petar V. Kokotovic]]\n* 1993: [[Edward J. Davison]]\n* 1996: [[Alberto Isidori]]\n* 1999: [[Brian D. O. Anderson]]\n* 2002: [[Lennart Ljung]]\n* 2005: [[Tamer Basar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/birkhauser/news?SGWID=0-40335-2-137602-0|title=Tamer Basar will receive the Giorgio Quazza Medal 2005|website=springer.com|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Graham Goodwin]]\n* 2011: [[Hidenori Kimura]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riken.jp/en/news_pubs/news/2010/20100827/|title=Hidenori Kimura wins Giorgio Quazza Medal|website=riken.jp|date=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n* 2014: [[David Mayne]]\n* 2017: [[Roger Brockett]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seas.harvard.edu/news/2016/08/roger-brockett-receive-lifetime-achievement-award|title=Roger Brockett to receive lifetime achievement award|website=harvard.edu|date=15 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2020: [[Walter Murray Wonham|W. Murray Wonham]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.utoronto.ca/news/university-professor-emeritus-murray-wonham-receives-the-giorgio-quazza-medal/|title=University Professor Emeritus Murray Wonham receives the Giorgio Quazza medal|website=utoronto.ca|date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n* [[IEEE Control Systems Award]]\n* [[Richard E. Bellman Control Heritage Award]]\n* [[Rufus Oldenburger Medal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Systems sciences awards]]\n", "name_user": "Poppopsun", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giorgio_Quazza_Medal"}
