July 2017\n|<ref name=\"Draft out\"/>\n|-\n|33\n|{{sort|33|DF}}\n!scope=\"row\"| {{flagicon|IND}} [[Gursimrat Singh]]\n| [[NorthEast United FC|NorthEast United]]\n| N/A\n| 23 July 2017\n|<ref name=\"Draft out\"/>\n|-\n| 9\n|{{sort|9|FW}}\n!scope=\"row\"| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Braulio N\u00f3brega]]\n|\n| Released\n|15 February 2018\n|<ref name=\"Segovia\"/>\n|-\n| 13\n|{{sort|13|MF}}\n!scope=\"row\"| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Edu Garc\u00eda]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhejiang Greentown F.C.|Zhejiang Greentown]]\n| $150,000\n| 23 February 2018\n|<ref name=\"Edu transfer\"/>\n|}\n\n==Pre-season and friendlies==\nBengaluru FC, having completed the squad selection at [[2017\u201318 ISL Players Draft]], arranged a 10-day pre-season training camp in [[Murcia]], [[Spain]] before facing [[North Korea]]n side [[April 25 Sports Club]]. During the tour, the blues were scheduled to face [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] side [[UCAM Murcia CF]] and [[UAE Pro League]] side [[Baniyas Club]] in the friendlies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/bengaluru-fc-set-to-train-in-spain-ahead-of-afc-cup-clash-4765592/|title=Bengaluru FC set to train in Spain ahead of AFC Cup clash|date=25 July 2017|work=[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]}}</ref> Later, a friendly against [[FC Cartagena]] was added as well. Bengaluru FC lost all three friendlies. During the AFC cup campaign, Bengaluru FC played [[India national under-19 football team]] and won with a solitary goal from [[Daniel Lalhlimpuia]].\n\nAfter the conclusion of [[2017 AFC Cup]] and before [[2017\u201318 Indian Super League season]], Bengaluru FC played two games against the former I-League rivals [[East Bengal F.C.]], [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]]. The first game on 25 October 2017 ended in a draw with [[Surabuddin Mollick]] and [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] scoring a goal each for their respective teams. Bengaluru FC won the second friendly 3\u20131. [[Udanta Singh]] scored a brace, whereas [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] scored the third goal. Bengaluru FC then played two friendlies against [[I-League]] debutant, [[Gokulam FC]], winning both games 2\u20130 and 3\u20131, respectively. Before the international break, Bengaluru FC played two more friendlies with [[Chennai City F.C.]], drawing the first 2\u20132, and winning the second friendly 6\u20131. In the final friendly before ISL, Bengaluru FC played yet another I-League side [[Minerva Punjab F.C.]], and lost the game 2\u20133.\n\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=9 August 2017\n|time= 19:00 [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|team1=[[UCAM Murcia CF]]\n|score=4\u20132\n|report=[https://twitter.com/bengalurufc/status/895358607025254400 Report]\n|team2=Bengaluru FC\n|goals1=Chevi {{goal|33}}<br/>[[Isidro Ros R\u00edos|Isi Ros]] {{goal|49}}<br/>[[Urko Arroyo|Arroyo]] {{goal|55}}<br/>Victor Garcia {{goal|85}}\n|goals2=[[Sunil Chhetri|Chhetri]] {{goal|8||56}}\n|location=[[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n|stadium=Pinatar Arena\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=L\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=12 August 2017\n|time= 19:00 [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|team1=[[FC Cartagena]]\n|score=3\u20130\n|report=[https://twitter.com/bengalurufc/status/896444884869042176 Report]\n|team2=Bengaluru FC\n|goals1=Kuki Zalazar {{goal|44}}<br/>[[Isaac Aketxe|Aketxe]] {{goal|52||55}}\n|goals2=\n|location=[[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n|stadium=[[La Manga Stadium]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=L\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=15 August 2017\n|time=19:00 [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|team1=[[Baniyas Club]]\n|score=3\u20130\n|report=[https://twitter.com/bengalurufc/status/897532270004781056 Report]\n|team2=Bengaluru FC\n|goals1=[[Harry Novillo|Novillo]] {{goal|17}}<br/>[[Saleh Al Menhali|Hamad]] {{goal|38}}<br/>Mubarak Al\u2013Mansoori {{goal|76}}\n|goals2=\n|location=[[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n|stadium=Pinatar Arena\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=L\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=1 September 2017\n|time=15:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=1\u20130\n|report=[http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-bengaluru-fc-beat-india-u-19-national-team/nuoz6oba5il81kwiz5cy67qah Report]\n|team2=[[India national under-19 football team|India U-19]]\n|goals1=[[Daniel Lalhlimpuia|Lalhlimpuia]] {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n|location=[[Bengaluru]]\n|stadium=[[Bangalore Football Stadium]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=25 October 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=1\u20131\n|report=[http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-ileague-bengaluru-fc-east-bengal-draw-pre-season/nic7eq777e23110r8wtx6uxrv Report]\n|team2=[[East Bengal F.C.|East Bengal]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] {{goal|80}}\n|goals2=\n* [[Surabuddin Mollick|Mollick]] {{goal|9}}\n|location=[[Bengaluru]]\n|stadium=[[Sree Kanteerava Stadium]]\n|attendance=0\n|referee=\n|result=D\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=27 October 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=3\u20131\n|report=[http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/bengaluru-fc-defeat-east-bengal-3-1-in-pre-season-friendly/hvnnp7ckfy391vmy15jphr4ri Report]\n|team2=[[East Bengal F.C.|East Bengal]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Udanta Singh|Udanta]] {{goal}} {{goal}}\n* [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n* [[Willis Plaza|Plaza]] {{goal}}\n|location=[[Bengaluru]]\n|stadium=[[Sree Kanteerava Stadium]]\n|attendance=0\n|referee=\n|result=W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=31 October 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=2\u20130\n|report=[https://twitter.com/bengalurufc/status/925326486625697795 Report]\n|team2=[[Gokulam FC]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Alwyn George|Alwyn]] {{goal}}\n* [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n|location=[[Bellary]]\n|stadium=Bengaluru FC residential academy ground\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=2 November 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=3\u20131\n|report=[https://twitter.com/bengalurufc/status/926090487211089920 Report]\n|team2=[[Gokulam FC]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Sunil Chhetri|Chhetri]] {{goal}}\n* [[Dimas Delgado|Dimas]] {{goal}}\n* [[Daniel Lalhlimpuia|Lalhlimpuia]] {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n|location=[[Bellary]]\n|stadium=Bengaluru FC residential academy ground\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=4 November 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=2\u20132\n|report=[https://thefangarage.com/articles/12850-pre-season-friendly-bengaluru-fc-held-to-a-draw-by-chennai-city-in-bellary-goalfest Report]\n|team2=[[Chennai City F.C.|Chennai City]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Daniel Lalhlimpuia|Lalhlimpuia]] {{goal}}\n* [[Sunil Chhetri|Chhetri]] {{goal| |pen. }}\n|goals2=\n* [[Gurpreet Singh (footballer)|G. Singh]] {{goal}}\n* [[Venyamin Shumeyko|Shumeyko]]{{goal}}\n|location=[[Bellary]]\n|stadium=Bengaluru FC residential academy ground\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=D\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=5 November 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=6\u20131\n|report=[https://twitter.com/bengalurufc/status/927060315073687552 Report] \n|team2=[[Chennai City F.C.|Chennai City]]\n|goals1=* [[Udanta Singh|Udanta]] {{goal}} {{goal}}\n* [[Sunil Chhetri|Chhetri]] {{goal}}\n* [[Braulio N\u00f3brega|N\u00f3brega]] {{goal}}\n* [[Erik Paartalu|Paartalu]] {{goal}}\n* [[Thongkhosiem Haokip|T. Haokip]] {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n* [[Ildar Amirov|Amirov]] {{goal}}\n|location=[[Bellary]]\n|stadium=Bengaluru FC residential academy ground\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|round = Friendly\n|date=8 November 2017\n|time=10:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=2\u20133\n|report=[https://twitter.com/Minerva_AFC/status/928131901562306560 Report]\n|team2=[[Minerva Punjab F.C.|Minerva Punjab]]\n|goals1=[[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] {{goal|43||63}}\n|goals2=[[Chencho Gyeltshen|Chencho]] {{goal|9||32||71}}\n|location=[[Bellary]]\n|stadium=Bengaluru FC residential academy ground\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|result=L\n}}\n\n==Competitions==\n===Indian Super League===\n{{main article|2017\u201318 Indian Super League season}}\n\n====Summary====\n=====November=====\n[[File:West Block Blues unfurling banner against Mumbai City FC.jpg|thumb|[[West Block Blues]] celebrating Bengaluru FC's participation in [[Indian Super League]].]]\nBengaluru made their [[Indian Super League|ISL]] debut against [[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]] on 19 November 2017 at the Sree Kanteerava Stadium in Bengaluru. Roca handed starts to new foreign signings, [[Edu Garc\u00eda]] and [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]]. Despite wonderful link up play between the forward duo of Chhetri and Miku, the hosts lacked finishing in the final third in the first half. There was hardly any opportunities created by Mumbai themselves as they chose to sit deep and Bengaluru dominated the game. In the second half, Bengaluru scored their first goal in ISL, courtesy a short corner routine, when Edu Garcia drilled one past former BFC man [[Amrinder Singh]] at the near post at the 67th minute. A defensive mix up in added time meant that Chhetri could get his name on the scoresheet and sealed a 2\u20130 victory for the blues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/bengaluru-v-mumbai-city/report/eiez7gtmt58nhn8q9ec3ex562|title=ISL 2017: Bengaluru FC 2\u20130 Mumbai City FC \u2013 Blues down Islanders in comfortable debut win|work=Goal.com|date=19 November 2017}}</ref> Bengaluru continued the form against [[Delhi Dynamos F.C.|Delhi Dynamos]], whom they defeated 4\u20131 with [[Erik Paartalu]] scoring a brace and [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] scoring his first goal for the club. However, they conceded a penalty late in the second half when [[John Johnson (footballer)|John Johnson]] was adjudged to have a handball inside the penalty area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-bengaluru-fc-delhi-dynamos/k4z5pl2xc6o911lncayf3nb9m|title=ISL 2017: Bengaluru FC set the early pace in the title race|work=Goal.com|first=Soham|last=Mukherjee|date=27 November 2017}}</ref> Bengaluru played their first away game of the season against [[FC Goa]] on 30 November 2017. In the action packed first half, [[Gurpreet Singh Sandhu]] was [[sent off]] and Bengaluru conceded three goals. With the team down to 10-men, Bengaluru managed to equalize score with Miku's brace at 3\u20133, but once Goa took the lead with [[Ferran Corominas|Coro]]'s hat-trick in 63rd minute, Bengaluru could not find an equalizer and tasted the first defeat of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/goa-v-bengaluru/ejyj38o1tlfmqb0tqywit0fai|title=ISL 2017: FC Goa 4\u20133 Bengaluru FC: Coro\u2019s hat-trick seals a thriller in Gaurs' favour|first=Anselm|last=Noronha|work=Goal.com|date=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=====December=====\nBengaluru FC kicked off the month of December with an away game against [[NorthEast United FC|NorthEast United]] on 8 December. Bengaluru FC made multiple changes, including bringing in [[Lalthuammawia Ralte]] to replace [[Gurpreet Singh Sandhu]], who was suspended for 2 games. [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] scored the only goal of the match to ensure the first away win of the season for Bengaluru FC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/northeast-united-v-bengaluru/report/elncwp2ji76mos2rf6lx0lxt6|title=ISL 2017: NorthEast United 0\u20131 Bengaluru FC \u2013 Miku wins it for Blues|date=8 December 2017|work=Goal.com}}</ref> Bengaluru played third consecutive away game against [[FC Pune City]] on 14 December. Facing the crowded schedule ahead, Bengaluru FC chose to start without [[John Johnson (footballer)|John Johnson]] and [[Edu Garc\u00eda]]. After lack of clear chances initially, Pune City took the lead from [[Adil Khan (footballer)|Adil Khan]]'s header. However, after Pune City's [[Baljit Sahni]] was sent-off after second yellow card, Bengaluru FC made the best of the situation and scored 3 goals in the second half with [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] scoring a brace and [[Sunil Chhetri]] scoring the final goal of the game in stoppage time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/pune-city-v-bengaluru/report/emgj0i3t55s7wpcaqgguqfgbu|title=ISL 2017: FC Pune City 1\u20133 Bengaluru FC: Miku brace fires visitors to the top of the league as Baljit Sahni sees red|date=14 December 2017|first=Ashish|last=Peter}}</ref> Bengaluru FC returned home against [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]] on 17 December 2017. Chennaiyin's stubborn defence contained Bengaluru FC attack and inflicted 1\u20132 defeat on the home team, with [[Sunil Chhetri]] scoring the only goal for Bengaluru.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/bengaluru-v-chennaiyin/report/en1fhlsa8pdq1us8mag9fuq22|title=ISL 2017: Bengaluru FC 1\u20132 Chennaiyin FC \u2013 Solid Super Machans down Blues|date=17 December 2017|work=Goal.com|first=Swapnaneel|last=Parasar}}</ref> Playing against the fellow debutant [[Jamshedpur FC]], Bengaluru conceded the late penalty to lose the game 0\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-bengaluru-fc-vs-jamshedpur-coppell-defensive-team/b4fkm8uo1bz61mzc3jqyfxhid|title=ISL 2017: Bengaluru FC have no answers to Steve Coppell\u2019s \u2018defensive\u2019 team|date=22 December 2017|work=Goal.com}}</ref> In a highly anticipated match, Bengaluru FC faced [[Kerala Blasters]] on the New Year's Eve. The first half remained goalless in the first half, but Bengaluru FC took the lead with [[Sunil Chhetri]]'s penalty in the second half. The stoppage time saw a flurry of goals, including a brace from [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] and Bengaluru won the game 1\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/kerala-blasters-v-bengaluru/report/eou4ervxdof4b2of8kux7sb56|title=ISL 2017/18: Kerala Blasters 1\u20133 Bengaluru FC: Miku and Sunil Chhetri stun Yellow Army into silence|first=Nisanth V|last=Easwar|work=Goal.com|date=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=====January=====\nBengaluru played the first game of 2018 at home against [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] on 7 January 2017 and won it 1\u20130 courtesy a goal from [[Sunil Chhetri]] in first half.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bengalurufc.com/bengaluru-back-winning-ways-fortress-atk-1-0/|title=Bengaluru back to winning ways at Fortress; down ATK 1\u20130|work=Bengalurufc.com|date=7 January 2018}}</ref> With upcoming fixtures of [[2018 AFC Cup]], Bengaluru FC rotated the squad against bottom-placed [[Delhi Dynamos FC]]. However, the rotation did not work out as Bengaluru faced 2\u20130 defeat away from home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-om/match/delhi-dynamos-v-bengaluru/report/er224vpcdjbfylt2mcmrfahka|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Delhi Dynamos 2\u20130 Bengaluru FC: Lions stun heavyweights to end seven-match winless run|first=Ashish|last=Peter|work=Goal.com|date=14 January 2018}}</ref> Still on the road, Bengaluru faced [[Mumbai City FC]] on 18 January 2018. [[Sunil Chhetri]] scored a brace against his former team and with a goal from [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]], Bengaluru registered a comfortable 3\u20131 win and climbed back to the top of the table.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-om/match/mumbai-city-v-bengaluru/report/erf3o1rygokx63p7oqf4abmui|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Mumbai City FC 1\u20133 Bengaluru FC \u2013 Blues do the double over the Islanders|first=Manasi|last=Pathak|date=18 January 2018|work=Goal.com}}</ref> Bengaluru secured another win at home against the highlanders, [[NorthEast United FC]] in the final game of January. [[Juanan]] and [[Sunil Chhetri]] scored a goal in each half to secure 3 points for the home team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/bengaluru-v-northeast-united/report/eswxyyv3edlkp7s9j5mr9guay|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Bengaluru FC 2\u20131 NorthEastUnited FC \u2013 Blues reclaim top spot after narrow win|first=Ashish|last=Peter|date=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====February=====\nOnce again Bengaluru FC started month playing [[ATK (football club)|ATK]], this time an away match. Bengaluru won the match 0\u20132. [[Jordi Figueras Montel]] scored an [[Own goal#Association football|own goal]] to give Bengaluru lead in 3rd minute. At 69th minute Bengaluru reduced ten men, when [[Rahul Bheke]]  received second yellow of the match and sent off. [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] scored second goal of the match at 83rd minute to keep Bengaluru FC top of the table.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bengalurufc.com/ten-man-bengaluru-complete-double-defending-champs-atk-2-0-win/|title=Ten-man Bengaluru complete double over defending champs ATK with 2\u20130 win|work=Bengalurufc.com |date=4 February 2018}}</ref> In top of the table clash, Bengaluru FC next played [[Chennaiyin FC]] away 6 February. [[Boithang Haokip]] gave the team an early lead, while [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] and [[Sunil Chhetri]] scored the goals in the second half to earn a decisive 3\u20131 victory in the South India derby and a lead of 7 points at the top.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-18-defending-chennaiyin-fc-bengaluru-fc/1b9vbi19wktst1rhep35ocsnfb|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Uncharacteristic defending lets down Chennaiyin FC against Bengaluru FC|work=Goal.com|first=Ashwin|last=Muralidharan}}</ref> Bengaluru continued the winning run against [[FC Goa]] at home on 9 February 2018. [[Edu Garc\u00eda]] secured the lead in the first half while [[Dimas Delgado]] scored his first goal for the team and sealed the game 2\u20130 in the second half, extending the team's winning streak to five games. With the win, Bengaluru FC also became the first team to confirm their spot in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/bengaluru-v-goa/report/evok2w4gj36z7uxudtomvfrze|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Bengaluru 2\u20130 Goa: Eagles better Gaurs to book semi-final berth|first=Manasi|last=Pathak|work=Goal.com|date=9 February 2018}}</ref> In another top of the table clash, Bengaluru FC faced [[FC Pune City]] at home on 16 February 2018. After conceding a goal in the first half, Bengaluru equalized with [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]]'s goal in the second half. Bengaluru were denied a clear penalty opportunity in the dying minutes of the game and settled for their first draw of the season in Indian Super League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-18-bengaluru-fc-pune-city-report-miku-equaliser/qwlj9crgzl6dzk4a9tpw764q|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Miku strike helps Bengaluru FC dampen FC Pune City spirits|first=Swapnaneel|last=Parasar|date=16 February 2018|work=Goal.com}}</ref> In the last away game of the season, Bengaluru FC faced [[Jamshedpur FC]] on 25 February 2018. [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] and [[Sunil Chhetri]] secured lead in the first half with a goal each and [[Gurpreet Singh Sandhu]] made crucial saves in the second half to earn a clean sheet and secured 2\u20130 win. With the win, Bengaluru FC also secured the top spot for the league stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/jamshedpur-v-bengaluru/report/ez672mdv299ipfl5pnnrkhkkq|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Gurpreet shines as Bengaluru FC sail past Jamshedpur FC|date=25 February 2018|first=Ritabrata|last=Banerjee}}</ref>\n\n=====March=====\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n| GK_nat  = IND | GK  = [[Gurpreet Singh Sandhu|Sandhu]]\n| RCB_nat = ESP | RCB = [[Juanan]]\n| CB_nat = AUS | CB = [[Erik Paartalu|Paartalu]]\n| LCB_nat = ENG | LCB = [[John Johnson (footballer)|Johnson]]\n| RWB_nat = IND | RWB = [[Rahul Bheke|Bheke]]\n| LWB_nat = IND | LWB = [[Boithang Haokip|Haokip]]\n| RCM_nat  = IND| RCM  = [[Lenny Rodrigues|Rodrigues]]\n| LCM_nat  = ESP| LCM =  [[Dimas Delgado|Delgado]]\n| RW_nat  =IND | RW  = [[Udanta Singh|Singh]]\n| LW_nat  =IND | LW  = [[Sunil Chhetri|Chhetri]]\n| CF_nat  = VEN| CF  = [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]]\n|caption=Lineup against [[Chennaiyin FC]] in [[2018 Indian Super League Final]]\n|image=striped\n}}\nIn the final game of the league stage, Bengaluru faced southern rivals [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]] at the home on 1 March 2018. The game remained deadlocked until [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] and [[Udanta Singh]] scored two goals in injury time to finish the league stage with a win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/match/bengaluru-v-kerala-blasters/report/ezl5m8ubq46dvpeanqx6y2i5m|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Blues strike twice in injury-time to break Blasters' resistance in southern derby|first=Ashish|last=Peter|date=1 March 2018|work=Goal.com}}</ref>\n\nBengaluru FC faced 4th placed [[FC Pune City]] in the semi-finals. Playing the first leg at away, Bengaluru had to settle for a goal-less draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-18-pune-city-bengaluru-match-report/19xru3l1tabr81rg7uxz7b85mg|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Stallions and Blues play out goal-less stalemate in cagey first-leg|date=7 March 2018|first=Ritabrata|last=Banerjee|work=Goal.com}}</ref> In the return leg played at home, Bengaluru FC defeated Pune City 3\u20131 to enter final in their debut [[Indian Super League|ISL]] season. Captain [[Sunil Chhetri]] scored his first [[hat-trick]] for Bengaluru FC. [[Jonatan Lucca]] scored the lone goal for Pune City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-18-the-man-for-the-big-occasions-inspirational/x75p4sv24sip1xzzo2ohh4cs3|title=ISL 2017\u201318: 'The man for the big occasions' \u2013 Inspirational Sunil Chhetri powers Bengaluru FC into the final!|date=12 March 2018|work=Goal.com|first=Ashwin|last=Muralidharan}}</ref>\n\nBengaluru FC faced [[Chennaiyin FC]] in [[2018 Indian Super League Final|the final]], played at Bengaluru FC's home [[Sree Kanteerava Stadium]]. Owing to [[Subhasish Bose]]'s suspension, Bengaluru opted to play three at the back with [[John Johnson (footballer)|John Johnson]], [[Erik Paartalu]] and [[Juanan]] playing in the defence and [[Rahul Bheke]] and [[Boithang Haokip]] playing as wing backs.<ref name=\"subhashish suspension\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/indian-super-league-final-three-man-defence-bengaluru-fc/1mpbiy7g73t3p1wz2ylvx4gb38|title=ISL Final: Three-man defence hasn\u2019t worked for Bengaluru FC|date=18 March 2018|first=Swapnaneel|last=Parasar}}</ref> Bengaluru took an early lead with [[Sunil Chhetri]] scoring a header from [[Udanta Singh]]'s assist in 9th minute. However, Chennaiyin quickly equalized via [[Ma\u00edlson Alves]]'s header in 17th minute from a corner. Bengaluru FC suffered a double blow as [[Dimas Delgado]] had to be substituted just before the half time due to an injury and Ma\u00edlson Alves scored the second goal just before the half time. Chennaiyin strengthened their lead as [[Raphael Augusto]] scored the third goal on the counter. Bengaluru FC's relentless attack in the dying minutes earned them a second goal by [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]], but Chennaiyin held on to the lead and emerged winner. The loss also ended Bengaluru FC's 15 match unbeaten streak across all tournaments and their first loss since their loss against [[Delhi Dynamos FC]] in January 2018.\n\nReacting to the defeat, [[Albert Roca]] said:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/albert-roca-perhaps-i-made-a-mistake-in-the-final|title=Albert Roca: Perhaps I made a mistake in the final|date=17 March 2018|work=[[Indian Super League]]}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|To concede from set-pieces is always disappointing. I don\u2019t blame the defence for this. It is my responsibility to change the system. But, I accept I made a mistake in the formation. Sometimes in football it is not the players who make the mistakes, but the coaches. And perhaps this time I made a mistake. I don\u2019t think we felt pressure, but Mailson scoring from two corners made a big difference. In a few minutes, the game changed. In football, you need players with his kind of experience to rise to the situation.}}\n\n====League stage====\n{{Football box collapsible |id=\"Bengaluru FC v Mumbai City\"\n|round = 1\n|date=19 November 2017\n|time= 20:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=2\u20130\n|report=[http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/bengaluru-go-top-of-the-table-with-win-over-mumbai Report]\n|team2=[[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Edu Garc\u00eda|Edu]] {{goal|67}}\n* [[Sunil Chhetri|Chhetri]] {{yel|83}} {{goal|90+3}} \n|goals2= \n* [[Gerson Vieira|Gerson]] {{yel|15}}\n|location=[[Bengaluru]]\n|stadium=[[Sree Kanteerava Stadium]]\n|attendance=17,796\n|referee=Aur\u00e9lien Juenkou\n|result=W\n|motm = [[Sunil Chhetri]] (Bengaluru FC) \n}}\n{{Football box collapsible |id=\"Bengaluru FC v Delhi Dynamos\"\n|round = 2\n|date=26 November 2017\n|time= 20:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=Bengaluru FC\n|score=4\u20131\n|report=\n|team2=[[Delhi Dynamos FC|Delhi Dynamos]]\n|goals1=\n* [[Erik Paartalu|Paartalu]] {{goal|24||45+3}}\n* [[Lenny Rodrigues|Lenny]] {{goal|57}} \n* [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] {{goal|87}} \n|goals2= \n* [[Kalu Uche|Kalu]] {{goal|86|pen.}} \n|location=[[Bengaluru]]\n|stadium=[[Sree Kanteerava Stadium]]\n|attendance= 18,248\n|referee= R Venkatesh\n|result=W\n|motm = [[Erik Paartalu]] (Bengaluru FC) \n}}\n{{Football box collapsible |id=\"FC Goa v Bengaluru FC\"\n|round = 3\n|date=30 November 2017\n|time= 20:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n|team1=[[FC Goa|Goa]]\n|score=4\u20133\n|report=[http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/corominas-hat-trick-helps-goa-beat-bengaluru-in-seven-goal-thriller Report]\n|team2=Bengaluru FC\n|goals1=\n* [[Ferran Corominas|Coro]] {{goal|16||33||63}}\n* [[Manuel Lanzarote|Lanzarote]] {{goal|40|pen.}} \n|goals2= \n* [[Lenny Rodrigues|Rodrigues]] {{yel|7}}\n* [[Miku (footballer)|Miku]] {{goal|21||60}}\n* [